For the bull signal condition, when `bearfvghigh[i] < bullfvglow[j]`, the bear FVG's top is below the bull FVG's bottom, meaning the bear FVG sits entirely beneath the bull FVG. The second condition checks if the bear FVG's bottom exceeds the bull FVG's top.

Let me trace through with concrete numbers: if bull is 100-105 and bear is 106-110, then `bearfvghigh(110) < bullfvglow(105)` is false, so no bull signal. But if bear is 98-99, then `bearfvghigh(99) < bullfvglow(105)` is true and `bearfvglow(98) > bullfvghigh(100)` is false, so still no signal. The conditions seem contradictory—I need to reconsider what these variables actually represent in the code.

Looking at the logic more carefully: if `bearfvghigh < bullfvglow` AND `bearfvglow > bullfvghigh`, then the bear FVG is entirely contained within the bull FVG. This is the BPR condition—detecting when a fair value gap forms inside another fair value gap.

The key insight is that I don't need to overthink the exact semantics. The implementation should check for non-overlapping FVGs of opposite types and trigger a signal in whichever direction the newer one points. I'll code it this way and let testing validate the logic.

Now examining the nested loop structure more carefully. When a new bull FVG appears, it's compared against all existing bear FVGs in the inner loop. The conditions check if the bear's upper boundary falls below the bull's lower boundary, or if the bear's lower boundary exceeds the bull's upper boundary—both cases indicate the FVG doesn't overlap with the current bull range.

Similarly, when a new bear FVG forms, it gets evaluated against all existing bull FVGs using the inverse logic to detect non-overlapping ranges.

